data.title: '5ft 6in and a face like a damaged potato - I wasn't exactly Sean Connery, was I?': A pint-sized street fighter with a giant talent, Bob Hoskins, who's died at 71, was a very unlikely star. That's why
data.meta_description: On the set of his final film, 2012's Outside Bet, Bob Hoskins was asked why, given his advancing age, he hadn't yet shuffled off into retirement.
data.text:
On the set of his final film, 2012’s Outside Bet, Bob Hoskins was asked why, given his advancing age, he hadn’t yet shuffled off into retirement.

‘I could, quite happily,’ he replied. ‘But there’s always someone who rings up and says: “Now Bob, before you go, there’s a cracking little swansong for you.”’ As to how he still coped with the physical demands of the job, he added: ‘I’m dead, I’m knackered, and I’ve got flu. If I survive this movie it’s gonna be a miracle, I tell you!’

The sentiment was classic Hoskins: honest, raw and cheerfully self-deprecating. In an industry full of cosseted prima donnas, he always worked his socks off, and never behaved like a diva. Both on camera and off, he was the most cheerful tough guy of British film. But now Bob Hoskins has died, aged 71.

In a statement released yesterday, his wife Linda and four children said he had died at hospital, surrounded by family members, following a bout of pneumonia. ‘We are devastated by the loss of our beloved Bob,’ it read.

Hoskins, who had in recent years appeared in Snow White And The Huntsman, Made In Dagenham, and Mrs Henderson Presents, had quit acting in 2012 after being diagnosed with Parkinson’s disease. Last night, his actress daughter, Rosa, 30, released a moving statement saying she had loved her ‘darling’ father ‘to the ends of the earth and he loved me back just the same’.

She repeated the advice he had given her: ‘laugh’; ‘be yourself’; ‘be flamboyant’; ‘don’t worry about other people’s opinions’; ‘get angry’; ‘whatever you do, always give it a good go’; ‘don’t take yourself too seriously’; ‘never, ever, ever, ever give up’ and ‘love with all your heart’.

As his daughter’s and other tributes attest, the passing of Hoskins marks a sad end to a unique, and hugely unlikely, celebrity journey.

Raised on the streets of North London, where he picked up his trademark gravelly accent, Hoskins overcame the limitations of birth and background to become one of the greatest screen stars of his generation.

In almost four decades treading Hollywood’s red carpets, where his broken and mis-shapen nose always looked splendidly out of place, he made more than 80 films. Among the most successful were 1980’s The Long Good Friday and 1988’s Who Framed Roger Rabbit, which made the then-incredible sum of £206 million.

Yet for all the acclaim and global success, not to mention the tens of millions of pounds he earned, Hoskins could never quite admit that his status as a ‘posh celebrity’ was anything other than a wonderful joke.

At the height of his fame, when he was earning £5 million per film, he described himself in interview as ‘five foot six, and cubic’ and jokily recalled how a critic had said he resembled ‘a testicle on legs’ with ‘a face like a damaged potato’. ‘I’m a short, fat, middle-aged man with a broken nose and a bald head,’ he remarked. ‘It’s not really Sean Connery, is it?’

Despite, or perhaps because of, his lack of outward glamour, his appeal was wide-ranging.

Hoskins was nominated for a Best Actor Oscar in 1986, for his portrayal of a small-town crook in Mona Lisa, but is perhaps more widely remembered as the gurning everyman who declared ‘It’s good to talk!’ in the BT adverts of the 1990s.

On stage, he held his own alongside Sir John Gielgud and Sir Jonathan Miller. On screen, he carried off roles as ruthless crooks, tender-hearted buffoons, and such real-life figures as Pope John XXIII, J. Edgar Hoover, and Mussolini.

This extraordinarily accomplished acting career began by accident. The son of a book-keeper, whose mother taught in a nursery school, he had grown up in gritty Finsbury Park. His battle-scarred face bore testament to the years he spent running with teenage gangs.

During one street fight, he was slashed with a knife across the bridge of the nose, marking him for life. In another, he was stabbed in the stomach, surviving only because it didn’t penetrate too deeply.

And however glamorous his life later became, memories of working-class London would always define him. ‘My accent is my identity,’ he once said. ‘It’s me. And that’s why I swear a f****** lot too. I like the way I talk, I like the way I am. It’s a matter of integrity and of necessity.’

After leaving school aged 15 (his dyslexia saw him written off as ‘stupid’) Hoskins was taken to meet gangsters Ronnie and Reggie Kray, who then ran East London’s underworld, at their mother’s council flat.

Couple: Actor Bob Hoskins and his second wife Linda arrive for a UK film premiere in London in May 2004

He chose, however, to resist the temptation to get rich through crime, and travelled to Israel, where he picked bananas on a kibbutz, before a spell in the merchant navy.

After that, there were stints as a steeplejack, hotel porter and circus fire eater. The trick, he said, was to hold his chin high, open his mouth wide, and keep the flames constantly moving so they didn’t burn his face.

But his dream was to act.

Everything changed one day in 1969, when the 26-year-old Hoskins found himself accompanying an actor friend to an audition for an amateur production at London’s Unity Theatre.

‘I was sat in the bar drinking, and someone came over to me and said “you’re next”,’ he recalled. ‘Being three-parts p***ed, I went in and auditioned. And the director of the play gave me the lead.

‘At the party after the first night, an agent called Sarah Randall came up to me and said: “Listen, you’ve got to take this up professionally.” I said: “Get us a job and I will.” And she did. I’ve never been out of work since.’

Co-stars: He appeared in Neverland in 2011 as Mr Smee alongside Anna Friel, who played Elizabeth Bonny

Told to have elocution lessons, Hoskins refused, proudly boasting in later life that he had never taken a single acting class, either. But it took a decade’s hard graft in theatre before his TV career took off.

The breakthrough came when, aged 36, he was cast in Dennis Potter’s Pennies From Heaven, a 1979 BBC drama which contained explicit sex scenes, the most controversial of which depicted Hoskins fully naked.

It caused outrage, but Hoskins found it hilarious. He later joked that the BBC was inundated with letters not of protest, but of sympathy.

His first major movie role was as the violent underworld kingpin Harold Shand in The Long Good Friday. Released in 1980, his terrifying portrayal of a London gangster facing a hostile takeover by foreign rivals was critically acclaimed.

Hollywood came calling. In 1982, Hoskins was sent the script for Francis Ford Coppola’s forthcoming film Cotton Club. But he presumed the job offer was from a friend, pulling his leg. ‘I said: “I’ll believe it’s real if he phones me up,”’ Hoskins recalled. ‘That night, at about half-past midnight, I got a call saying: “Hello, this is Francis Coppola.’’’

Still thinking it was a joke, Hoskins replied: ‘Well I’m Henry VIII and you’ve just woken the bloody kids up.’

Coppola was not discouraged.

Hoskins's most recent appearance was in Snow White and the Huntsman, released in 2012. He is seen right

By 1986, Hoskins was being nominated for Oscars, and dividing his time between LA and North London. Then came Who Framed Roger Rabbit (he claimed its pneumatic cartoon blonde Jessica was his sexiest co-star), Mermaids, with Cher (‘they had to stand me on a box to kiss her’) and a Disney remake of Peter Pan called Hook, with Dustin Hoffman and Robin Williams.

By the age of 50, in 1992, Hoskins was a serious Hollywood player. Robert de Niro used to drop round for dinner. But Hoskins never lost an ability to poke fun at pretence.

Hoskins once recalled, for example, how, at a script reading for Hook, the megastars around him started downplaying their lofty status by discussing their rare failures.

Spielberg apologised for his awful Pearl Harbour film, 1941. Hoffman said sorry for Ishtar, a legendary flop. Robin Williams pleaded forgiveness for Cadillac Man.

When it came to be Bob’s turn, he puffed out his chest: ‘Well, I ain’t apologising for f****** NOTHING!’

In truth, of course, Hoskins made his fair share of turkeys. But, true to his word, he wouldn’t apologise.

Asked about those ubiquitous and brash BT adverts, he told an interviewer: ‘I can think of half-a-million reasons why doing those adverts is a good idea, and all of them have the Queen’s head on.’

The plain-spoken demeanour, and lack of pretence — he claimed never to watch his films — is exactly what endeared him to the British public. It would, however, be a mistake to say his fame was entirely plain sailing.

His first wife, schoolteacher Jane Livesey, with whom he had two children, divorced him in 1979, after learning that he had shared a mud hut with a female actress while filming Zulu Dawn in South Africa.

In 1980, Jane gave an interview accusing him of domestic abuse. ‘Bob is a very violent man,’ she claimed. He denied hitting her, but admitted having been a terrible husband and father.

‘I was concentrating on making my name as an actor. Every time I went home, the children were six inches taller. I had missed great parts of their lives.’

The divorce saw him ‘crippled with grief’ and he suffered a nervous breakdown. He recovered by writing The Bystander, a play about a man having a breakdown.

That he survived past 40, he always said, was thanks to second wife Linda Banwell, a blonde former schoolteacher whom he met on the day of Prince Charles’s wedding.

‘I had made up this ideal partner in my mind, and I walked into this pub, and there she was,’ he recalled. ‘I was totally ruthless. I was in so much debt that I was living in the back of a Jeep . . . I parked it outside Linda’s house, and said: “Are you going to leave me out here then?” She just didn’t have a chance.’

The couple were soon smitten. ‘Home isn’t houses, and it isn’t a country,’ he said. It’s family. To me, anyway, and Linda’s my home.’

They enjoyed more than three happy decades together, and had two children, Rosa and Jack, who were at Bob’s bedside this week with Linda. Also there were Alexander and Sarah, from his first marriage.
